## Clone the project

### Backend (Ruby on Rails)

This application runs better on Linux. If you have a Windows system, try WSL.

1. Fork the Git repository from here:   
   [https://github.com/renjiniravath/AmazeZoneAPI](https://github.com/renjiniravath/AmazeZoneAPI)   
2. Clone the forked repository on your system: 

git clone https://github.com/\<your\_username\>/AmazeZoneAPI 

3. Open the project in RubyMine/VSCode. Also, run the following in the terminal:  
   cd AmazeZoneAPI  
4. Give execute permission to entrypoint.sh by typing in the following command  
   chmod \+x entrypoint.sh  
5. Run the following command to start up the application using docker-compose

   docker-compose up

   

   

	Note: If you are working on Windows, you might encounter an error which looks like this.  
	![][image1]  
	To tackle this comment the line entrypoint: /app/entrypoint.sh on docker-compose.yml and try docker-compose up again.

6. Open a different terminal in the same folder and run the following command to run migrate database:

		docker-compose exec web rails db:migrate

- Run this command after creating a migration to run it.  
- web is the docker-compose service that is associated with the backend application. Whenever a command needs to be run inside the backend container (The Amazezone backend application composed in Ruby on Rails), docker-compose exec web can be prepended to the command and executed while the service is up and running. i.e, while docker-compose up is running in a different terminal.  
  Refer docker-compose exec: [https://docs.docker.com/engine/reference/commandline/compose\_exec/](https://docs.docker.com/engine/reference/commandline/compose_exec/)   
7. If at any point, you are adding a new gem, you should instruct docker-compose to rebuild by stopping the existing service by using Ctrl \+ C on the terminal running docker-compose up, and then running docker-compose up \--build  
8. Import [this Postman collection](https://documenter.getpostman.com/view/5763209/2s9YJaWNQM) into your Postman desktop app and try out sign up, login and product endpoints.  
9. The backend application will be running on the port 3000\.

## Implement associations

[Active record associations](https://guides.rubyonrails.org/association_basics.html) are useful to link the models using a real-life like connection between them. For example, a user has\_many credit cards or a transaction belongs\_to a user. These relationships can be easily specified using associations, and doing so makes it easier to access or create linked models. We will be doing these as we progress through this exercise.

![][image2]

For this exercise the base project comes with Users and Products already implemented, as opposed to letting you create Product like last time. The reason is that although scaffolding can help us create the backend of our application, the frontend *views* (or in this case, React-Typescript pages) won’t be generated by scaffolding, and that would make the exercise much bigger if we implement all the modules. 

Q: How is scaffolding different in a Rails API only application?

A: In short, there are no views, the controllers return data in JSON and get data through HTTP requests. Read [this article](https://edgeguides.rubyonrails.org/api_app.html) to get a deeper understanding.

In an API only Rails application, a certain configuration in config/application.rb and the corresponding comment tells us what exactly is Rails API only mode. Check the file in your project to see the configuration.

![][image3]

## Products

Even though it’s already implemented, let’s take a look at how **Products** works.

### Backend

To generate the Product scaffolding for backend, the below command was run.   
**You do not have to run any commands/add any code that pertains to Product as that module is already completed in your clone.** The steps are given below for reference purposes.

[docker-compose exec](https://docs.docker.com/engine/reference/commandline/compose_exec/) web rails [generate scaffold](https://guides.rubyonrails.org/v3.2/getting_started.html#getting-up-and-running-quickly-with-scaffolding) Product name:string category:string quantity:integer price:integer

This generates some code, the major ones discussed below.

config/routes.rb

resources :products

This line in routes redirects any HTTP request to a url starting with **/products** to functions in the ProductsController.

controllers/products\_controller.rb

class ProductsController \< ApplicationController  
    before\_action :set\_product, only: %i\[show update destroy\]  
    
    \# GET /products  
    def index  
      @products \= Product.all  
    
      render json: @products  
    end  
    
    \# GET /products/1  
    def show  
      render json: @product  
    end  
    
    \# POST /products  
    def create  
      @product \= Product.new(product\_params)  
    
      if @product.save  
        render json: @product, status: :created, location: @product  
      else  
        render json: @product.errors, status: :unprocessable\_entity  
      end  
    end  
    
    \# PATCH/PUT /products/1  
    def update  
      if @product.update(product\_params)  
        render json: @product  
      else  
        render json: @product.errors, status: :unprocessable\_entity  
      end  
    end  
    
    \# DELETE /products/1  
    def destroy  
      @product.destroy  
    
      head :no\_content  
    end  
    
    private  
      \# Use callbacks to share common setup or constraints between actions.  
      def set\_product  
        @product \= Product.find(params\[:id\])  
      end  
    
      \# Only allow a list of trusted parameters through.  
      def product\_params  
        params.require(:product).permit(:name, :category, :quantity, :price)  
      end  
  end

The functions in the controller are list all, view only one, create, update, and delete respectively.   
See that the responses are always JSON and are returned with an HTTP status code.

We need to make sure a user is authorized before they add a product. To solve this problem, we added this line below the first before\_action.

before\_action :authenticate\_request, only: %i\[index show create update destroy\]

Other files like a model, migration, test files were also generated as a part of the scaffolding. We shall look into some of those in the next module (Credit Card).

### Frontend

To see the product functionality in action, sign up a user, login and click on “View Products”.

If you are completely new to Javascript, it might be helpful going through the links mentioned in the following discussion. Students who have played around with React can scan through the material and skip to the part where we get back to doing the exercise.

**General Structure**  
App.tsx has the routes, linking browser urls to React components. We can see how pages like signup, login and the product functions are mapped to their corresponding urls.  
![][image4]  
src/components and src/pages contain the React components. We keep all product components and the creditcard, transactions components that follow in this exercise in the src/components folder because these components are technically different parts of the same “grouping” (either Product, CreditCard or Transaction) that work together to form a full feature. src/pages have standalone pages like Signup, Login, Home and Main. Take a look into the Login component to see how authentication is implemented.

Note: The above discussion sheds light on the difference between Javascript and Rails when it comes to the amount of convention that needs to be followed. We have learned that Rails is a convention over configuration framework. React/Javascript does not lean as much as Rails into that concept. We can have a bigger autonomy on things like folder structure and component naming as long as they are imported by name and location in files that they will be used in. (React is a library, and not a framework)

Now, let’s take a look into how Products work in the front end. Product’s functionality is spread across 4 files, ProductList.tsx, ProductDetail.tsx, ProductForm.tsx, and ProductDelete.tsx which carry out self explanatory functions. We will go through a quick run down of the ProductList.tsx file. 

The file starts with the required imports. We import the React object, and two functions useState and useEffect, which we will discuss soon. We make use of a library called axios for making easier HTTP requests, and that is imported next. We use a component named Link when we want to redirect to a different page without a browser refresh. You can read more about react-router-dom [here](https://reactrouter.com/en/main). 

After the React component is declared, we see that the useState function is used to create a products array and a setProducts function. Read more about useState and state variables [here](https://react.dev/reference/react/useState). In short, useState returns a state variable and a function to change that particular state variable. When a state variable’s value is changed using the associated function, React rerenders that page. State variable, setState functions, and [props](https://react.dev/learn/passing-props-to-a-component) form the basis of React.  

[useEffect](https://react.dev/reference/react/useEffect) function is used to perform certain tasks when certain conditions are achieved. In this project, we are exclusively using useEffect only to call some APIs and load values when a React component is successfully loaded (mounted). 

In this component, we are using useEffect to call the product list endpoint to get the list of products and then we store the list in the state variable products, by using the function setProducts. Optional read on [promises, async and await.](https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Learn/JavaScript/Asynchronous/Promises)

Now we get to the easier parts. This project uses inline styling due to simplicity and ease of use linked strongly with the smaller size of the project. For bigger projects, it is almost always a good decision to avoid inline styling.

A React component usually returns something called [JSX](https://react.dev/learn/writing-markup-with-jsx), which is just a way of writing markup using Javascript. JSX is very much HTML-like but with Javascript in between.  
![][image5] 

Inside return, we can see different tags with inline styling. We can also see that the products array is iterated using the map function to create list-items for each product, with each list-item styled to look like a row with product name, product category, product price, and links to go to “show”, “edit” and “delete”.

We can also see a link outside the unordered list, which would direct to the “New Product” page.

Go through the ProductDetail, ProductForm, and ProductDelete components to understand how these components work. See that ProductForm component works for both adding and updating products.

## CreditCards

We will walk this module together. The code is very similar to Products, but you will have to do Transactions alone, so make sure you get your lessons right\!

### Backend

While keeping docker-compose up running, run the following two commands in a separate terminal window.

Generate the backend scaffolding using the command below.  
docker-compose exec web rails generate scaffold CreditCard name:string card\_number:string expiration\_date:date cvv:string user:references

Run migrations.  
docker-compose exec web rails db:migrate

Add this line to config/routes.rb  
resources :credit\_cards

We make some changes to the code generated in credit\_cards\_controller to make sure that a user can view/create/update/delete/list only their and no one else’s credit cards. We add a check comparing the current user to credit\_card.user to achieve this. 

  controllers/credit\_cards\_controller.rb

  \# GET /credit\_cards  
  def index  
    @credit\_cards \= current\_user.credit\_cards

    render json: @credit\_cards  
  end

  \# GET /credit\_cards/1  
  def show  
    if @credit\_card.user \== current\_user  
      render json: @credit\_card  
    else  
      render json: { error: 'Access denied' }, status: :forbidden  
    end  
  end

  \# POST /credit\_cards  
  def create  
    @credit\_card \= CreditCard.new(credit\_card\_params)  
    @credit\_card.user \= current\_user

    if @credit\_card.save  
      render json: @credit\_card, status: :created, location: @credit\_card  
    else  
      render json: @credit\_card.errors, status: :unprocessable\_entity  
    end  
  end

  \# PATCH/PUT /credit\_cards/1  
  def update  
    if @credit\_card.user \== current\_user  
      if @credit\_card.update(credit\_card\_params)  
        render json: @credit\_card  
      else  
        render json: @credit\_card.errors, status: :unprocessable\_entity  
      end  
    else  
      render json: { error: 'Access denied' }, status: :forbidden  
    end  
  end

  \# DELETE /credit\_cards/1  
  def destroy  
    if @credit\_card.user \== current\_user  
      @credit\_card.destroy  
    else  
      render json: { error: 'Access denied' }, status: :forbidden  
    end  
  end

We also need to add authentication to this controller by adding this line:  
  before\_action :authenticate\_request

Now, we need to implement associations in the models.

models/credit\_card.rb

class CreditCard \< ApplicationRecord  
  belongs\_to :user  
end

models/user.rb

class User \< ApplicationRecord  
  has\_many :credit\_cards  
  has\_secure\_password

  validates :email\_address, presence: true, uniqueness: true  
  validate :email\_format

  private

  def email\_format  
    unless /\\A\[\\w+\\-.\]+@\[a-z\\d\\-.\]+\\.\[a-z\]+\\z/i.match?(email\_address)  
      errors.add(:email\_address, 'has an invalid format')  
    end  
  end  
end

A validation is done for email format, but that’s already in the code that you started working on.

components/CreditCardForm.tsx

import React, { useState, useEffect } from 'react';  
import axios from 'axios';  
import { useNavigate, useParams } from 'react-router-dom';

const CreditCardForm: React.FC \= () \=\> {  
  const { id } \= useParams();  
  const \[creditCard, setCreditCard\] \= useState({  
    name: '',  
    card\_number: '',  
    expiration\_date: '',  
    cvv: '',  
  });

  const navigate \= useNavigate();

  useEffect(() \=\> {  
    async function fetchCreditCardData() {  
      const response \= await axios.get(  
        \`http://localhost:3000/credit\_cards/${id}\`,  
        {  
          headers: {  
            Authorization: localStorage.getItem('auth\_token'),  
            Accept: 'application/json',  
            'Content-Type': 'application/json',  
          },  
        }  
      );  
      setCreditCard(response.data);  
    }  
    if (id) {  
      fetchCreditCardData();  
    }  
  }, \[id\]);

  const handleChange \= (e: React.ChangeEvent\<HTMLInputElement\>) \=\> {  
    const { name, value } \= e.target;  
    setCreditCard({ ...creditCard, \[name\]: value });  
  };

  const handleSubmit \= async (e: React.FormEvent) \=\> {  
    e.preventDefault();  
    if (id) {  
      // Update existing credit card  
      await axios.put(\`http://localhost:3000/credit\_cards/${id}\`, creditCard, {  
        headers: {  
          Authorization: localStorage.getItem('auth\_token'),  
          Accept: 'application/json',  
          'Content-Type': 'application/json',  
        },  
      });  
    } else {  
      // Create a new credit card  
      await axios.post('http://localhost:3000/credit\_cards', creditCard, {  
        headers: {  
          Authorization: localStorage.getItem('auth\_token'),  
          Accept: 'application/json',  
          'Content-Type': 'application/json',  
        },  
      });  
    }  
    // Redirect to credit card list page or do something else after submission  
    navigate('/credit\_cards');  
  };

  const formStyle \= {  
    fontFamily: 'Arial, sans-serif',  
    // backgroundColor: '\#f0f0f0',  
    padding: '20px',  
    height: '100vh',  
    width: '100vw',  
    display: 'flex',  
    flexDirection: 'column',  
    alignItems: 'center',  
    justifyContent: 'center',  
  };

  const headerStyle \= {  
    fontSize: '24px',  
    marginBottom: '20px',  
  };

  const labelStyle \= {  
    display: 'block',  
    marginBottom: '10px',  
  };

  const inputStyle \= {  
    width: '100%',  
    padding: '8px',  
    marginBottom: '10px',  
    border: '1px solid \#ddd',  
    borderRadius: '4px',  
  };

  const buttonStyle \= {  
    backgroundColor: '\#007bff',  
    // color: 'white',  
    padding: '10px 20px',  
    border: 'none',  
    borderRadius: '4px',  
    cursor: 'pointer',  
  };

  return (  
    \<div style={formStyle}\>  
      \<h1 style={headerStyle}\>  
        {id ? 'Edit Credit Card' : 'Create Credit Card'}  
      \</h1\>  
      \<p\>Enter exp date in yyyy-MM-dd format. Not validated\</p\>  
      \<form onSubmit={handleSubmit}\>  
        \<label style={labelStyle}\>  
          Name:  
          \<input  
            type="text"  
            name="name"  
            value={creditCard.name}  
            onChange={handleChange}  
            style={inputStyle}  
          /\>  
        \</label\>  
        \<label style={labelStyle}\>  
          Card Number:  
          \<input  
            type="text"  
            name="card\_number"  
            value={creditCard.card\_number}  
            onChange={handleChange}  
            style={inputStyle}  
          /\>  
        \</label\>  
        \<label style={labelStyle}\>  
          Expiration Date:  
          \<input  
            type="text"  
            name="expiration\_date"  
            value={creditCard.expiration\_date}  
            onChange={handleChange}  
            style={inputStyle}  
          /\>  
        \</label\>  
        \<label style={labelStyle}\>  
          CVV:  
          \<input  
            type="text"  
            name="cvv"  
            value={creditCard.cvv}  
            onChange={handleChange}  
            style={inputStyle}  
          /\>  
        \</label\>  
        \<button type="submit" style={buttonStyle}\>  
          {id ? 'Update' : 'Create'}  
        \</button\>  
      \</form\>  
    \</div\>  
  );  
};

export default CreditCardForm;

components/CreditCardDetails.tsx

import React, { useEffect, useState } from 'react';  
import { useParams, Link } from 'react-router-dom';  
import axios from 'axios';

interface CreditCard {  
  id: number;  
  name: string;  
  card\_number: string;  
  expiration\_date: string;  
  cvv: string;  
}

const CreditCardDetail: React.FC \= () \=\> {  
  const { id } \= useParams();  
  const \[creditCard, setCreditCard\] \= useState\<CreditCard | null\>(null);

  useEffect(() \=\> {  
    async function fetchData() {  
      const response \= await axios.get(  
        \`http://localhost:3000/credit\_cards/${id}\`,  
        {  
          headers: {  
            Authorization: localStorage.getItem('auth\_token'),  
            Accept: 'application/json',  
            'Content-Type': 'application/json',  
          },  
        }  
      );  
      setCreditCard(response.data);  
    }

    fetchData();  
  }, \[id\]);

  const containerStyle \= {  
    fontFamily: 'Arial, sans-serif',  
    // backgroundColor: '\#f0f0f0',  
    padding: '20px',  
    height: '100vh',  
    width: '100vw',  
  };

  const headerStyle \= {  
    fontSize: '24px',  
    marginBottom: '20px',  
  };

  const productInfoStyle \= {  
    border: '1px solid \#ddd',  
    borderRadius: '4px',  
    padding: '20px',  
    // backgroundColor: 'white',  
  };

  if (\!creditCard) {  
    return (  
      \<div style={containerStyle}\>  
        \<h1 style={headerStyle}\>Credit Card Detail\</h1\>  
        \<p\>Loading...\</p\>  
      \</div\>  
    );  
  }

  return (  
    \<div style={containerStyle}\>  
      \<h1 style={headerStyle}\>Credit Card Detail\</h1\>  
      \<div style={productInfoStyle}\>  
        \<p\>  
          \<strong\>Name:\</strong\> {creditCard.name}  
        \</p\>  
        \<p\>  
          \<strong\>Card Number:\</strong\> {creditCard.card\_number}  
        \</p\>  
        \<p\>  
          \<strong\>Expiration Date:\</strong\> {creditCard.expiration\_date}  
        \</p\>  
        \<p\>  
          \<strong\>CVV:\</strong\> {creditCard.cvv}  
        \</p\>  
      \</div\>  
      \<div style={{ marginTop: '20px' }}\>  
        \<Link to={\`/credit\_cards/${id}/edit\`}\>Edit\</Link\>  
        \<Link to={\`/credit\_cards/${id}/delete\`} style={{ marginLeft: '10px' }}\>  
          Delete  
        \</Link\>  
      \</div\>  
    \</div\>  
  );  
};

export default CreditCardDetail;

    padding: '20px',  
    marginTop: '3%',  
    width: '100vw',  
    height: '100vh',  
  };

  const confirmationStyle \= {  
    fontSize: '16px',  
    marginBottom: '20px',  
  };

  const handleDelete \= async () \=\> {  
    if (window.confirm('Are you sure you want to delete this credit card?')) {  
      await axios.delete(\`http://localhost:3000/credit\_cards/${id}\`, {  
        headers: {  
          Authorization: localStorage.getItem('auth\_token'),  
          Accept: 'application/json',  
          'Content-Type': 'application/json',  
        },  
      });  
      navigate('/credit\_cards');  
    }  
  };

  return (  
    \<div style={containerStyle}\>  
      \<h1\>Delete Credit Card\</h1\>  
      \<p style={confirmationStyle}\>  
        Are you sure you want to delete this credit card?  
      \</p\>  
      \<button onClick={handleDelete} style={buttonStyle}\>  
        Delete Credit Card  
      \</button\>  
    \</div\>  
  );  
};

export default CreditCardDelete;

Now we need to link these components to browser urls. For that we need to add the following block to App.tsx

\<Route path='/credit\_cards' element={\<PrivateRoute /\>}\>  
	\<Route path='' element={\<CreditCardList /\>} /\>  
	\<Route path=':id' element={\<CreditCardDetail /\>} /\>  
	\<Route path='new' element={\<CreditCardForm /\>} /\>  
	\<Route path=':id/edit' element={\<CreditCardForm /\>} /\>  
	\<Route path=':id/delete' element={\<CreditCardDelete /\>} /\>  
\</Route\>

Make sure that these components have been imported to App.tsx

Save the changes, and the updates should be visible and working in the browser.

## Transactions

For simplicity, we are assuming that a user can purchase only one product at a time. The product quantity can be selected by the user (e.g., whether they want 5 units of that product or 10), and the total price will be determined accordingly. 

Note: Scroll to the bottom of the file to see the contents of the blanks.

### Goals

1. **Generate scaffold for transactions**

Remember to add the docker-compose prefix and add references to user, credit\_card and product.

3. **Introduce ability to purchase products**  
     
1. Going through the transaction endpoints in the Postman [collection](https://documenter.getpostman.com/view/5763209/2s9YJaWNQM) could be a good starting point.  
2. Add some products and credit cards using the application.  
3. We need to add a Link element to each product row in the ProductList component which says “Purchase”. Clicking on this Link element should take the user to a /transactions/new, where they can purchase that product. Try to see if you can send the product id of the product being purchased, by using the [Link](https://ui.dev/react-router-pass-props-to-link) component.  
4. In the /transactions/new page, the user gets to choose:  
   1. The quantity they are buying (integer)  
   2. See and change the product (Use [select](https://react.dev/reference/react-dom/components/select#controlling-a-select-box-with-a-state-variable) for this. Call the product list endpoint and then populate the select options.)   
   3. The credit card they intend to use. (Use select. Call the credit card list endpoint and then populate the select options.)  
   4. The user should also be able to see the total cost of the purchase in a read-only input field.  
5. Refer to the Postman collection to see what parameters are sent as a part of the POST body.   
6. Inside the create function in transactions\_controller.rb, we need to create the transaction\_number using a random string of length 10, and then store the current user id as the transaction’s user id.

  **4\. Introduce ability to view purchase history**

1. A user should be able to see a list of their transactions. Only transactions belonging to the current user should be listed. Add a check in the backend.  
2. A page to edit a transaction is not required.

The backend after transactions would look something like this: [https://github.com/renjiniravath/AmazeZoneAPI/tree/transactions](https://github.com/renjiniravath/AmazeZoneAPI/tree/transactions) 

The frontend after transactions can look different for everyone, depending upon one’s coding style. However, a sample one would look like this: [https://github.com/qureshi-ali/AmazeZone-Frontend/tree/transactions](https://github.com/qureshi-ali/AmazeZone-Frontend/tree/transactions) 

Keep in mind that this is a very bare bone application and has a large number of areas where it can improve. For example, while listing transactions, it would be really helpful if the page showed product names instead of product ids, as we did in the sample provided. Also, the code will be cut down if an approach to keep CSS in a different file was followed. But since this is a smaller application, we have followed inline styling. Interfaces and types, if kept on different files, can be imported to other files as per need, and that is definitely a region where improvements can be made. Although all these are sensible improvements, that would come with a steeper learning curve.
